<p><b>The penal colony of Cayenne</b> (<a href="/wiki/French_language" title="French language">French</a>: <i>Bagne de Cayenne</i>), commonly known as <b>Devil's Island</b> (<i>Île du Diable</i>), was a notorious prison of the 19th and 20th centuries. It operated at several locations in <a href="/wiki/French_Guiana" title="French Guiana">French Guiana</a>. Opened in 1852, it is notorious for being used for internal exile of French political prisoners during that period,<sup id="cite_ref-prison_closure_date_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-prison_closure_date-1"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> the most famous of which was Captain <a href="/wiki/Alfred_Dreyfus" title="Alfred Dreyfus">Alfred Dreyfus</a>. The system was closed down in 1953.</p>
<p></p>
